reviewText: The Good/I've been a fan of Ian's for the past 40 years or so & truly think he is a musical genius. I admire someone who's not afraid to take a great song they've written & redo it to get a new flavor out of it. Ian's given lots of his songs a fresh wash here & most Tull fans will approve. The audio is excellent & this dvd is a delight to listen to. The symphony is well mixed, unlike some rock/symphony dvds where you can hardly hear them & Ian has them front & center in this show. They're not just an add on. I also really enjoyed the interview with Ian. It's a great look into this rock icons views & musings. 5 starsThe Bad/Video quality is only fair/average, & the editing is mostly fine but includes some (fortunately few) special effects. 3 starsThe Ugly/Amazon says this is NTCS but the disc they sent me is Region 0 PAL. My blu-ray player did not like this disc at all. To wit/ tried to start concert from the audio selection screen, this killed the playback. Start again, this time starting the concert from the main menu. Viewed the show up to the intermission, then it kicked straight to Ian's interview after which the playback died again. Start again, going to 'chapters' menu to start concert at end of the intermission. There was also a 'master audio' option in the bonus section that kills the playback. I got to watch the entire 3 hours of this dvd but it was a struggle, very screwed up. 0 starsThe 4 stars is probably a little generous, but I'm willing to presume the war my player had with this disc won't happen to most people.

reviewText: This DVD is very entertaining and the lengthy Ian Anderson interview is very interesting. It would only have been better if songs from 1977-1979 had been included: Songs From the Wood, Heavy Horses and Stormwatch. These were three of my favorite albums. Overall, it is well worth the money spent.
summary: Outstanding performance by Tull leader, Ian Anderson

reviewText: In the most recent "A New Day" magazine Ian complains that the video of this concert runs straight through without any breaks for commentary. That is the best aspect of this DVD.  I don't know if this is a quirk on my DVD only, but the 47 min. interview with Ian comes at the intermission. That's a bit disconcerting.The version of Aqualung has to be seen and heard to be believed.  Purists will hate it!  Those with open minds will love it.  The second half of the show is more energetic than the first.  That doesn't mean the first half is dull.The band is exellent although guitarist Florian Opahle, "the toy boy of the band," looks out of place with the others.  Performance wise he's no Martin Barre, but he plays Martin's parts very well.The biggest flaw I found was in the editing of the concert tape.  The producers could have used at least one more day in the edit suite, but that's a nitpick on my part.  That's the reason for the four rating.

reviewText: First and most important: it is NOT Jethro Tull!It is a show of Ian Anderson with a group of session musicians and a symphonic orchestra (Frankfurt Philharmonic, to be exact). If you are looking for Jethro Tull live DVD, you've got a wrong disk. This show is as different from traditional rock concert almost as, say, "Aqualung" is different from "Divinities - 12 dances with God". But if you are looking for DVD with good music, then you have found one!The tracklist includes songs from IA solo albums and JT classics:01. Eurology02. Calliandra Shade03. Skating Away On The Thin Ice Of A New Day04. Up The Pool05. We Five Kings06. Life Is A Long Song07. In The Grip Of Stronger Stuff08. Wond'ring Aloud09. Griminelli's Lament10. Cheap Day Return11. Mother Goose12. Bouree13. Boris Dancing14. Living In The Past15. Pavane16. Aqualung17. God Rest Ye Merry Gentlemen18. My God19. Budapest20. Locomotive BreathYou will be amazed by some of the arrangements (Aqualung in particular) and the way Ian Anderson communicates with the audience. BTW, I enjoyed the interview section of this DVD almost as much as the concert itself!I am sure that if you like different kinds of music, you will love this DVD.
